      <listAnnotation type="miscellaneous">
         <note xml:id="misc_268" type="description">
            <term id="misc_268-term">april 1799 ?</term>
            <gloss id="misc_268-gloss" target="#misc_268-term">
               <p>Probably John Davy's hand; John is dating the experiments on this page that were part of the research for Davy's paper that he sent to William Nicholson in April 1799, published as 'Experiments and Observations on the Silex Composing the Epidermis, or External Bark, and Contained in Other Parts of Certain Vegetables', in Nicholson's A Journal of Natural Philosophy (April 1799-March 1800).</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_267" type="description">
            <term id="misc_267-term">bonnet cane</term>
            <gloss id="misc_267-gloss" target="#misc_267-term">
               <p>From one of the rattan palms used for Malcacca Cane - Calamus rotang.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_188" type="description">
            <term id="misc_188-term">Digitalis</term>
            <gloss id="misc_188-gloss" target="#misc_188-term">
               <p>Foxgloves</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_109" type="description">
            <term id="misc_109-term">aeriform</term>
            <gloss id="misc_109-gloss" target="#misc_109-term">
               <p>Meaning having the form or nature of air; gaseous. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_308" type="description">
            <term id="misc_308-term">traite elementaire</term>
            <gloss id="misc_308-gloss" target="#misc_308-term">
               <p>Davy confuses Lavoisier's Traité élémentaire de chimie and Fourcroy's Elémens d’histoire naturelle et de chimie in much the same way he did for his June 1798 'Essay'; See Frank James, 'Humphry Davy's Early Chemical Knowledge', Ambix (2019), pp.306-307.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_362" type="description">
            <term id="misc_362-term">Spirit Lamp</term>
            <gloss id="misc_362-gloss" target="#misc_362-term">
               <p>An alcohol burner or spirit lamp is a piece of laboratory equipment used to produce an open flame.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_281" type="description">
            <term id="misc_281-term">clayfields airholder</term>
            <gloss id="misc_281-gloss" target="#misc_281-term">
               <p>A machine invented by William Clayfield (1772-1837) between 1795 and 1800 used to measure how much nitrous oxide could be inhaled by a patient; it is described in Davy's Researches, Chemical and Philosophical (1800).</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_286" type="description">
            <term id="misc_286-term">syrup of violets</term>
            <gloss id="misc_286-gloss" target="#misc_286-term">
               <p>Violet syrup and juice was used by chemists as an early form of litmus paper to indicate the PH, changing colour in the presence of acids and bases.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_388" type="description">
            <term id="misc_388-term">I stated to you in April</term>
            <gloss id="misc_388-gloss" target="#misc_388-term">
               <p>Davy wrote to William Nicholson on 17 April 1799 about his discovery that gaseous oxyd of azote (Nitrous oxide) is 'respirable' when freed from nitrous gas (nitric oxide). This may be a previously unidentified draft letter fragment addressed to Nicholson. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_883" type="description">
            <term id="misc_883-term">The Royal Society of London</term>
            <gloss id="misc_883-gloss" target="#misc_883-term">
               <p>The Royal Society, formally The Royal Society of London for Improving Natural Knowledge, is a learned society and the United Kingdom's national academy of sciences. Founded on 28 November 1660, it was granted a royal charter by King Charles II and is the oldest continuously existing scientific academy in the world.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_390" type="description">
            <term id="misc_390-term">Nicholson's Chemistry</term>
            <gloss id="misc_390-gloss" target="#misc_390-term">
               <p>This may refer to either William Nicholson's the two-volume A Dictionary of Chemistry (1795) or The First Principles of Chemistry (1790, second edition, 1792, third 1796). See Frank James, 'Humphry Davy's Early Chemical Knowledge', Ambix (2019), p. 305.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_392" type="description">
            <term id="misc_392-term">a smiling man</term>
            <gloss id="misc_392-gloss" target="#misc_392-term">
               <p>Person, untraced, inhaling nitrous oxide.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_317" type="description">
            <term id="misc_317-term">retort</term>
            <gloss id="misc_317-gloss" target="#misc_317-term">
               <p>In a chemistry laboratory, a retort is a device used for distillation or dry distillation of substances. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_393" type="description">
            <term id="misc_393-term">M<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                   rend="superscript">r</hi> T</term>
            <gloss id="misc_393-gloss" target="#misc_393-term">
               <p>Person, untraced.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_394" type="description">
            <term id="misc_394-term">Miss. T.</term>
            <gloss id="misc_394-gloss" target="#misc_394-term">
               <p>Person, untraced. Miss T's experiences after inhaling nitrous oxide are not included in Davy's published version Researches, Chemical, and Philosophical.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_494" type="description">
            <term id="misc_494-term">Spurge</term>
            <gloss id="misc_494-gloss" target="#misc_494-term">
               <p>Euphorbias - a very large and diverse genus of flowering plants, commonly called spurge, which all share the feature of having a poisonous, latex-like sap and unique floral structures.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_837" type="description">
            <term id="misc_837-term">To St Michaels Mount</term>
            <gloss id="misc_837-gloss" target="#misc_837-term">
               <p>This is a version of a poem published in Robert Southey's Annual Anthology, i (1799), 172-6.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_004" type="description">
            <term id="misc_004-term">Belerion</term>
            <gloss id="misc_004-gloss" target="#misc_004-term">
               <p>A name for Land's End (the shining land) in Cornwall.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
